(38, 'component content', 0, '"<h1>KCM Orchestra Performance<\\/h1><h2>Bach Double Violin Concerto BWV 1043 1st Mvt<\\/h2><iframe width=\\"100%\\" height=\\"360\\" src=\\"http:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/embed\\/9a9rndysU_A?feature=player_detailpage\\" frameborder=\\"0\\" allowfullscreen><\\/iframe>"', 'margin: 0 auto; ', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Bach Double Violin Concerto BWV 1043 1st Mvt', 'http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9a9rndysU_A'),
(39, 'content', 0, '"<h1>Guitar Types<\\/h1>\\n<p>There are various types of guitars with origins from the Lute, ancient stringed instrument played like the guitar as far back as 16th and 17th century. Some of the varieties of the guitar are;<\\/p>\\n<ul>\\n<li>Acoustic Steel&nbsp;&nbsp; with 6 or 12 strings<\\/li>\\n<li>Classical guitar with nylon strings on slightly thicker neck<\\/li>\\n<li>Electric guitar usually thin with thinner gauge strings compared to acoustic guitar<\\/li>\\n<li>Acoustic\\/Electric usually takes shape of Acoustic guitar with equalizer style<\\/li>\\n<li>Electric Bass Guitar 4, 5 or 6 strings common for jazz licks<\\/li>\\n<li>Double bass for classical or jazz styles normally classical style played with bow<\\/li>\\n<\\/ul>\\n<h1>What it entails<\\/h1>\\n<p>Guitar is one of the most played instrument of all yet least understood as it takes hours of practice and study to understand it holistically. As the saying goes &ldquo;It&rsquo;s easiest to learn but hardest to master.&rdquo; In principle, study of the guitar is divided in two phrases; &ldquo;Cognitive&rsquo;&rsquo; mind oriented learning and&nbsp; Motoric&rdquo; that&rsquo;s practical application, this is same for other instruments but guitar tends to be more involving and one has to be very creative on an instrument that&rsquo;s 3 in 1 that&rsquo;s rhythmic, melodic and&nbsp; percussive. Bottom line is lots of patience is required yet an intelligent approach to practice cannot be wished away, that&rsquo;s why no matter how much one is able to do they&rsquo;ll need some lessons at some stage.<\\/p>\\n<h1>Why take lessons?<\\/h1>\\n<p>To a large extent humanity has some element of musicality within them whether they&rsquo;re in tune or not the latter certainly would need more lessons where they&rsquo;ve shown a desire to learn an instrument , As I said earlier , guitar is rhythmic, melodic &amp; percussive. To incorporate either one of this, Proper direction and understanding holistically is key. This involves structures e.g scales, arpeggios and chordal manouvres that need to be understood within a given phrase. Chords add colour and richness in rhythm to a piece. While scales determine proper melodic and harmonic knowledge when applied correctly. Proper technique can only be learnt during lesson, this enhances good articulation and dexterity and a more controlled rhythm.<\\/p>\\n<h1>Music Types<\\/h1>\\n<p>Guitar can be applied on any type or genre as long as a chord is splashed on a piece. Though the most outstanding styles appropriate for guitar are; Rock, blues, jazz , R&amp;B, reggae, rhumba, chakacha and most Latin American and South African styles to mention but just a few.<\\/p>\\n<p>One has to understand each technique and approach, although culture has to be engrained also to determine success of each one of these styles.<\\/p>"', '', '2013-07-17 18:00:00', '2013-07-17 19:00:00', '', 'academics/departments/string/guitar'),
(40, 'component profiler', 0, '"<div class=\\"img\\"><img src=\\"\\/images\\/staff\\/manasseh-uzele.jpg\\" alt=\\"MANASSEH UZELE\\" align=\\"middle\\" \\/><\\/div>\\r\\n<div class=\\"profile-tabs\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"tabs\\">\\r\\n<div id=\\"forte\\">\\r\\n<h1>MANASSEH UZELE<\\/h1>\\r\\n<h2>CLASSICAL, ACOUSTIC AND BASS GUITAR AND DOUBLE BASS<\\/h2>\\r\\n<p>manasseh.uzele@conservatoire.co.ke<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/div>\\r\\n<div id=\\"quote\\">\\r\\n<p>Manasseh is a Congolese guitarist with over 20 years experience teaching, mentoring and developing performers among them Sauti Sol, Susana Owiyo, Eric Wainaina and Khamadi Ojiambo. He has performed and toured extensively with the Uzeles locally and overseas in Germany, Canada and Switzerland, playing guitar and the baritone and valve trombone.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Manasseh offers instruction in classical, bass, rhythm and electric guitars in classical and contemporary styles. He also prepares candidates for the internationally recognized Associated Board of the Royal Schools of Music (ABRSM) practical exams. He founded the Acoustic Alchemy concert which takes place annually to showcase the skills his students have gained in the classroom. The concert has gained extensive popularity within Nairobi and will be unveiled with the name &ldquo;Fret Venture&rdquo; in 2014.<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/div>\\r\\n<\\/div>\\r\\n<\\/div>"', '', '2012-11-29 06:35:09', '2012-11-29 06:35:09', 'MANASSEH UZELE', NULL),
(41, 'component profiler', 0, '"<div class=\\"img\\"><img src=\\"\\/images\\/staff\\/christine-kamau.jpg\\" alt=\\"CHRISTINE KAMAU\\" align=\\"middle\\" \\/><\\/div>\\r\\n<div class=\\"profile-tabs\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"tabs\\">\\r\\n<div id=\\"forte\\">\\r\\n<h1>CHRISTINE KAMAU<\\/h1>\\r\\n<h2>PIANO, SAXOPHONE, TRUMPET<\\/h2>\\r\\n<p>christine.kamau@conservatoire.co.ke<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/div>\\r\\n<div id=\\"quote\\">\\r\\n<p>Christine is an afro-jazz trumpeter\\/composer and an upcoming artist in the Kenyan jazz music scene. In April 2012, she released her debut album &ldquo;This is for You&rdquo;, an 8-track instrumental afro-jazz album of her own compositions tirelessly worked on with the help of Cameroonian music producer Romeo Kouemeni. It includes the tracks &lsquo;Conversations&rsquo;, and &lsquo;This is for You&rsquo; that have been receiving radio airplay.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Christine grew up in Nakuru, Kenya and began showing signs of musicianship at an early age. Her parents encouraged her by enrolling her for lessons at age 11 to study music theory and classical piano. She followed on with learning the trumpet at The Kenya Conservatoire of Music under Kagema Gichuhi. She is a multi-instrumentalist who also loves playing the alto saxophone and tenor trombone.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Her love for African-jazz began while on a trip to South Africa for a music audition where she discovered Jazz music by African horn players like Jonas Gwangwa, Moses Khumalo, Ratau Mike, amongst others. Inspired by the exposure to their music and enthused by their fusion of jazz with distinctive South African grooves she began to write and arrange her own music. She draws her inspiration from a spiritual calling to praise God in her life coupled by the affection for songwriting and composition. Christine has performed at various local music events in including the monthly festival Blankets and Wine, Jazz Under the Stars, Sierra Ladies of Jazz and the Afro-jazz Concert Series amongst others. Christine has also been featured in a new musical program by the BBC world service titled &lsquo;Africa Beats&rsquo;, a series that showcases emerging music talent from Africa. You can find her performing alongside her band comprised of remarkably gifted instrumentalists: Isaac Khakula (Bass Guitar), Ken Simiyu (Keyboards), Daniel Macharia (Drums), Matthew Makumi (Guitars), Tim Riungu (Tenor Sax) and Emmanuel Kute (Alto Saxophone\\/Flute).<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/div>\\r\\n<\\/div>\\r\\n<\\/div>"', '', '2012-11-29 06:35:09', '2012-11-29 06:35:09', 'CHRISTINE KAMAU', NULL),
(42, 'component profiler', 0, '"<div class=\\"img\\"><img src=\\"\\/images\\/staff\\/wandiri-karimi.jpg\\" alt=\\"WANDIRI KARIMI\\" align=\\"middle\\" \\/><\\/div>\\r\\n<div class=\\"profile-tabs\\">\\r\\n<div class=\\"tabs\\">\\r\\n<div id=\\"forte\\">\\r\\n<h1>WANDIRI KARIMI<\\/h1>\\r\\n<h2>CLASSICAL AND ACOUSTIC GUITAR<\\/h2>\\r\\n<p>wandiri.karimi@conservatoire.co.ke<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/div>\\r\\n<div id=\\"quote\\">\\r\\n<p>Karimi has a great passion for the development of the Arts industry in Kenya, including but not limited to music. She has taught guitar since 2005 and continues to offer lessons to students in several schools throughout Nairobi.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>With an LLM (Intellectual Property) from the University of South Africa, she shares a great enthusiasm for the development of a greater understanding of intellectual property rights for all artists. She is the Legal and Administration Director for Ennovator Music and has undertaken several professional development ventures including an Artist Management Course at the Alliance Francaise, and Intellectual Property Course at the British Council and several ABRSM practical examinations. She is the Co-founder of the Nairobi Kinanda Arts Festival and has been a participant in the Tusker All Stars Project as a band member.<\\/p>\\r\\n<\\/div>\\r\\n<\\/div>\\r\\n<\\/div>"', '', '2012-11-29 06:35:09', '2012-11-29 06:35:09', 'WANDIRI KARIMI', NULL),
